      <listPerson>
         <person xml:id="person_951">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Jesus</forename>
               <surname>Christ</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="c. 6-4 BC"/>
            <death when="AD 30 or 33"/>
            <note>The central figure of Christianity; a first-century Jewish preacher and religious leader.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_029">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Thomas</forename>
               <surname>Beddoes</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1760"/>
            <death when="1808"/>
            <note>A politically radical (Jacobin) chemist and physician who in the 1790s established the Medical Pneumatic Institution in Bristol to investigate the physiological and possible curative effects of all the gases discovered during the eighteenth century. Between late 1798 and early 1801 he employed Davy as Superintendent of the Institution.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_736">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">William</forename>
               <surname>Clayfield</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1772"/>
            <death when="1837"/>
            <note>A Bristol man of science and a colleague of Davy's at the Medical Pneumatic Institution.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_030">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Antoine-Laurent</forename>
               <surname>Lavoisier</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1742"/>
            <death when="1794"/>
            <note>French chemist and tax farmer (for which he was guillotined). Developed a new nomenclature for chemistry (much of which is still in use today) and argued strongly against the existence of phlogiston. Davy read some of his writings while in Cornwall which he then opposed and throughout his career maintained an ambivalent attitude towards Lavoisierian chemisty. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_018">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">David</forename>
               <surname>Hartley</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1705 (bap.)"/>
            <death when="1757"/>
            <note>Associationist, whose work argued that the vibrations of nerves created sensation. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_275">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <surname>Prometheus</surname>
            </persName>
            <note>In Greek mythology, defied the Olympian gods by stealing fire and giving it to humans.</note>
         </person>
      </listPerson>
      <listAnnotation type="miscellaneous">
         <note xml:id="misc_523" type="description">
            <term id="misc_523-term">The Gospel</term>
            <gloss id="misc_523-gloss" target="#misc_523-term">
               <p>There are four gospels in the New Testament of the Bible.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_335" type="description">
            <term id="misc_335-term">Mahometans</term>
            <gloss id="misc_335-gloss" target="#misc_335-term">
               <p>A historical term used to denote a follower of Muhammad, the Islamic prophet; the word Muslim is more acceptable today. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_878" type="description">
            <term id="misc_878-term">Ignes fatui</term>
            <gloss id="misc_878-gloss" target="#misc_878-term">
               <p>The plural of ignis fatuus, or will-o'-the wisp. An atmospheric ghost light seen by travellers at night, especially over bogs or marshes.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_829" type="description">
            <term id="misc_829-term">Letter to Davies Giddy, 12th November 1798</term>
            <gloss id="misc_829-gloss" target="#misc_829-term">
               <p>This is a letter to Davies Giddy, dated 12 November 1798, published in Paris, Life, i, 64-66 and the Collected Letters of Sir Humphry Davy, i, 14-16</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_879" type="description">
            <term id="misc_879-term">Table of the Combination of Light</term>
            <gloss id="misc_879-gloss" target="#misc_879-term">
               <p>Draft of a table which appeared in Th. Beddoes 'Contributions to Physical and Medical Knowledge' Bristol 1799, page 91</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_272" type="description">
            <term id="misc_272-term">Eudiometer</term>
            <gloss id="misc_272-gloss" target="#misc_272-term">
               <p>A eudiometer is a laboratory device that measures the change in volume of a gas mixture following a physical or chemical change. An early version was used by Priestley in the discovery of oxygen.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_103" type="description">
            <term id="misc_103-term">Pyrophorus</term>
            <gloss id="misc_103-gloss" target="#misc_103-term">
               <p>A substance the ignites spontaneously after exposure to air, one of the earliest known is that of Homberg.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_109" type="description">
            <term id="misc_109-term">aeriform</term>
            <gloss id="misc_109-gloss" target="#misc_109-term">
               <p>Meaning having the form or nature of air; gaseous. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
