      <listNym type="chemical">
         <nym xml:id="chemical_022">
            <form>oxygene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: O</p>
               <p>Now known as oxygen. Oxygen is a colourless, odourless, tasteless gas essential to living organisms.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_039">
            <form>phosoxygen</form>
            <def>
               <p>Davy's working name for the combination of light and oxygen. He published his theories in a collection of essays entitled On Heat, Light, and the Combinations of Light, On Phos-oxygen and its Combinations (1799).</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_042">
            <form>baryte</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: BaSO4</p>
               <p>In modern nomenclature, a mineral consisting of barium sulphate. In Davy's terminology it might have been equivalent to baryta, BaO.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_516">
            <form>Phosphuret of strontian</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Sr3P2</p>
               <p>In modern terms this is strontium phosphide, an inorganic compound of strontium and phosphorus. The compound looks like black crystalline material.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_514">
            <form>Strontian</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Sr</p>
               <p>Old terminology for strontium, an alkaline earth metal, a soft silver-white yellowish metallic element that is highly chemically reactive. The metal forms a dark oxide layer when it is exposed to air.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_016">
            <form>muriatic acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: HCl</p>
               <p>Hydrochloric acid. Davy also refers to this as muriatic gas and marine acid.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_041">
            <form>boric acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: B(OH)3</p>
               <p>A compound of boron, oxygen, and hydrogen. Davy often refers to this as boracic acid.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_010">
            <form>lime</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CaO</p>
               <p>Commonly known as quicklime or burnt lime, calcium oxide is a widely used chemical compound. It is a white, caustic, alkaline, crystalline solid at room temperature.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_051">
            <form>phosphate of lime</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Ca3(PO4)2</p>
               <p>Tricalcium phosphate (sometimes abbreviated TCP) is a calcium salt of phosphoric acid.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_513">
            <form>Sulphate of Strontian</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: SrSO4</p>
               <p>The sulfate salt of strontium, in modern terms strontium sulphate.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_190">
            <form>barytes</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: BaSO4</p>
               <p>Now known as barium sulphate (BaSO4), a white crystalline solid, occurring as the mineral barites.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_299">
            <form>muriate of barytes</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: BaCl2</p>
               <p>Now known as barium chloride. It is a white powder, highly toxic, and imparts a yellow-green coloration to a flame.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_052">
            <form>gaseous oxide of azote</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: N2O</p>
               <p>Nitrous oxide. Davy initially refered to nitrous oxide as 'gaseous oxide of azote', but changed to 'nitrous oxide' on the discovery that the gas was respirable.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_072">
            <form>hydrocarbonate </form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H2 + CO</p>
               <p>Hydrogen mixed with carbon monoxide. </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_007">
            <form>hydrogene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H</p>
               <p>Now known as hydrogen. Hydrogen is the lightest element and, at standard conditions, is a gas of diatomic molecules. It is colourless, odourless, tasteless, non-toxic, and highly combustible.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_058">
            <form>carbonic acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CO2 or H2CO3 </p>
               <p>Now known as Carbon dioxide (CO2), or a solution of carbon dioxide in water (H2CO3). </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_017">
            <form>nitrogene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: N</p>
               <p>Now known as nitrogen. A colourless and odourless gas, nitrogen is non-combustible and non-toxic. Davy also refers to this as azote.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_054">
            <form>carbon</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: C</p>
               <p>A non-metallic and tetravalent element. Well-known allotropes include graphite, diamond, amorphous carbon, and fullerenes.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_512">
            <form>Earths</form>
            <def>
               <p>Referring to metal oxides, compounds that contain a single element that is bonded with oxygen.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_055">
            <form>caustic alkalis</form>
            <def>
               <p>The hydrate of potassium (caustic potash) or sodium (caustic soda).</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_056">
            <form>fluoric acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: HF</p>
               <p>Hydrofluoric acid. A solution of hydrogen fluoride in water.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_012">
            <form>mercury</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Hg</p>
               <p>Also known as quicksilver. A heavy, silvery element, mercury is the only metallic element that is known to be liquid at standard temperature and pressure.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_009">
            <form>lead</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Pb</p>
               <p>A heavy metal that is denser than most common materials. Lead is soft and malleable, and also has a relatively low melting point.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_038">
            <form>tin</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Sn</p>
               <p>A silvery-coloured metal, tin is soft enough to be cut with little force, and a bar of tin can be bent by hand with little effort.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_008">
            <form>iron</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Fe</p>
               <p>A strong, hard, magnetic silvery-grey metal. It is, by mass, the most common element on Earth, just ahead of oxygen, forming much of Earth's outer and inner core.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_201">
            <form>zinc</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Zn</p>
               <p>A a slightly brittle metal at room temperature and has a shiny-greyish appearance when oxidation is removed.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_060">
            <form>manganese</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Mn</p>
               <p>A hard, brittle, silvery metal, often found in minerals in combination with iron. Manganese was first isolated in the 1770s.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_059">
            <form>wolfram</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: W</p>
               <p>Also known as tungsten. Tungsten is an exceptionally strong refractory metal. It was identified as a new element in 1781 and first isolated as a metal in 1783.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_030">
            <form>potash</form>
            <def>
               <p>An alkaline substance consisting largely of impure potassium carbonate. In October 1807, Davy decomposed potash using electricity, revealing the previously unknown element potassium.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_035">
            <form>soda</form>
            <def>
               <p>An alkaline substance obtained from the ashes of marine or salt-impregnated plants, especially species of Salsola. Davy decomposed soda to reveal its elemental sodium.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_003">
            <form>ammonia</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: NH3</p>
               <p>An inorganic chemical compound of nitrogen and hydrogen. Ammonia is a colourless gas with a distinct pungent smell.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_011">
            <form>magnesia</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: MgO</p>
               <p>A white hygroscopic solid mineral that occurs naturally as periclase and is a source of magnesium.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_138">
            <form>phosacids</form>
            <def>
               <p>Davy used the phos to refer to these acids as chemical compounds that contained light as an element.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_078">
            <form>elastic fluid</form>
            <def>
               <p>A descriptive term for a gas, emphasising its elastic quality of spontaneous expansion.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_048">
            <form>nitrous oxide</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: N2O</p>
               <p>Later known as 'laughing gas'. Davy discovered that nitrous oxide was respirable when not contaminated with nitric oxide (NO). Davy researched into the physiological effects of nitrous oxide.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_151">
            <form>phosphorus</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: P</p>
               <p>A non-metallic chemical element of the nitrogen family. A colourless, semitransparent, soft, waxy solid.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_064">
            <form>liver of sulphur</form>
            <def>
               <p>A mixture of potassium sulphide, potassium polysulphide, potassium thiosulphate, and potassium bisulphide.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_037">
            <form>sulphur</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: S</p>
               <p>Pure sulphur is a tasteless, odourless, brittle solid that is pale yellow in colour, a poor conductor of electricity, and insoluble in water.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_352">
            <form>green vitriol</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: FeSO4</p>
               <p>Iron(II) sulphate, also known as ferrous sulphate.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_166">
            <form>iron oxide </form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Fe2O3</p>
               <p>Oxide of iron. A dark red solid which occurs as the mineral haematite and as the main component of rust.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_067">
            <form>sulfurous acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H2SO3</p>
               <p>Sulphuric acid. A mineral acid composed of the elements sulphur, oxygen, and hydrogen. </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_264">
            <form>iron(II) chloride</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: FeCl2</p>
               <p>A chemical compound also known as ferrous chloride. The compound is white, but typical samples are often off-white.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_143">
            <form>nitric acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: HNO3</p>
               <p>A highly corrosive mineral acid. The compound is colourless, but samples tend to acquire a yellow cast over time due to decomposition into oxides of nitrogen</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_068">
            <form>sulphite</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: SO</p>
               <p>Any salt or ester of sulphurous acid, containing the ions SO32- or HSO3- (hydrogen sulphite) or the groups -SO3 or -HSO3. The salts are usually soluble crystalline compounds.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
      </listNym>
